.TH _PRINTF 3 "NOVEMBER 28, 2025" "Manual" "Custom C Library Functions"
.SH NAME
_printf - formatted output conversion

_printf writes to `stdout` and returns the number of characters printed, just like the libc implementation.

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.B int _printf (const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fB_printf\fR() function is a simplified custom implementation of the standard C library function \fBprintf\fR().
It writes a character string to the standard output, processing variadic arguments according to the conversion directives found in the \fIformat\fR string.

A conversion directive begins with the % symbol and is followed by a specifier that determines how the corresponding argument should be formatted.

.SS Conversion Specifiers
The following conversion specifiers are currently supported:
.TP
.B c 
Prints the \fIint\fR argument as a single character. 
.TP 
.B s
Prints the \fIchar *\fR (string) argument up to the terminating null byte (\fB\e0\fR). If the pointer is \fBNULL\fR, it prints "(null)". 
.TP 
.B %
Prints a single percent characer ('%').
.TP 
.B d, i
Prints the \fIint\fR argument in signed decimal format.
.TP
.B u
Prints the \fIunsigned int\fR argument in unsigned decimal format.
.TP
.B o
Prints the \fIunsigned int\fR argument in unsigned octal format.
.TP
.B x
Prints the \fIunsigned int\fR argument in unsigned hexadecimal format, using lowercase letters (\fBa-f\fR).
.TP
.B X
Prints the \fIunsigned int\fR argument in unsigned hexadecimal format, using uppercase letters (\fBA-F\fR).
.TP
.B p
Prints the \fIvoid *\fR (pointer) argument in hexadecimal format (e.g., \fB0x7ffe637541f0\fR).

.SS FLAGS, FIELD WIDTH, PRECISION, LENGTH MODIFIER 
Currently, this version of \fB_printf\fR() does not support flags, minimum field width, precision, or length modifiers (e.g. \fB#\fR, \fB+\fR, \fB0\fR, \fBl\fR, \fBh\fR).

.SH RETURN VALUE  
Upon successful return, the \fB_printf\fR() function returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used to end output to strings).
.PP
If an output errors occurs or if the format string is \fBNULL\fR, the function returns \fB-1\fR.
.PP
If an unknown conversion specifier is encountered (e.g., \fB%z\fR), \fB_printf\fR() prints the literal sequence (\fB%z\fR) and returns the count of the characters printed (\fB2\fR).

.SH EXAMPLES
.EX
/* Example 1: To print a character and a integer/ 
#include main.h 
int chars_printed = _printf("The year is %d and the initial is %c\n", 2025, 'J');
/Output: The year is 2025 and the initial is J */
_printf("Characters printed in this example: %d\n", chars_printed)
/Output: Characters printed in this example: 38 */
.EE
.EX
/* Example 2: Basic types and return value check /
#include "main.h"
int count_d = _printf("The year is %d and the initial is %c\n", 2025, 'J');
/ Output: The year is 2025 and the initial is J /
_printf("Characters printed in this example: %d\n", count_d);
/ Output: Characters printed in this example: 38 /
.EE
.EX
/ Example 2: Unsigned and Hexadecimal /
unsigned int num = 12345;
_printf("Decimal: %u | Octal: %o | Hex (lower): %x | Hex (upper): %X\n", num, num, num, num);
/ Output: Decimal: 12345 | Octal: 30071 | Hex (lower): 3039 | Hex (upper): 3039 /
.EE

